aa(lp171
VSo, I want to tell you a story \u2014
p172
aVI want to take you on a little trip.
p173
aVImagine yourself, if you can,
p174
aVyou're a young woman in Africa, you're going to the hospital or clinic.
p175
aVYou go in for a test
p176
aVand you find out that you're pregnant, and you're delighted.
p177
aVAnd then they give you another test
p178
aVand they tell you you're HIV-positive, and you're devastated.
p179
aVAnd the nurse takes you into a room,
p180
aVand she tells you about the tests
p181
aVand HIV and the medicines you can take
p182
aVand how to take care of yourself and your baby,
p183
aVand you hear none of it.
p184
aVAll you're hearing is, "I'm going to die,
p185
aVand my baby is going to die."
p186
aVAnd then you're out on the street, and you don't know where to go.
p187
aVAnd you don't know who you can talk to,
p188
aVbecause the truth is, HIV is so stigmatizing
p189
aVthat if you partner, your family, anyone in your home,
p190
aVyou're likely to be thrown out
p191
aVwithout any means of support.
p192
aVAnd this \u2014 this is the face and story
p193
aVof HIV in Africa today.
p194
aa(lp195
VBut we're here to talk about possible solutions
p196
aVand some good news.
p197
aVAnd I want to change the story a little bit.
p198
aVTake the same mother, and the nurse, after she gives her her test,
p199
aVtakes her to a room.
p200
aVThe door opens and there's a room full of mothers, mothers with babies,
p201
aVand they're sitting, and they're talking, they're listening.
p202
aVThey're drinking tea, they're having sandwiches.
p203
aVAnd she goes inside, and woman comes up to her and says,
p204
aV"Welcome to mothers2mothers.
p205
aVHave a seat. You're safe here.
p206
aVWe're all HIV-positive.
p207
aVYou're going to be okay. You're going to live.
p208
aVYour baby is going to be HIV-negative."
p209
aa(lp210
VWe view mothers
p211
aVas a community's single greatest resource.
p212
aVMothers take care of the children, take care of the home.
p213
aVSo often the men are gone.
p214
aVThey're working, or they're not part of the household.
p215
aVOur organization, mothers2mothers,
p216
aVenlists women with HIV
p217
aVas care providers.
p218
aVWe bring mothers who have HIV,
p219
aVwho've been through these PMTCT programs
p220
aVin the very facilities,
p221
aVto come back and work side by side with doctors and nurses
p222
aVas part of the health care team.
p223
aVThese mothers, we call them mentor mothers,
p224
aVare able to engage women
p225
aVwho, just like themselves, pregnant with babies,
p226
aVhave found out about being HIV-positive,
p227
aVwho need support and education.
p228
aVAnd they support them around the diagnosis
p229
aVand educate them about how to take their medicines,
p230
aVhow to take care of themselves,
p231
aVhow to take care of their babies.
p232
aVConsider: if you needed surgery,
p233
aVyou would want the best possible technical surgeon, right?
p234
aVBut if you wanted to understand
p235
aVwhat that surgery would do to your life,
p236
aVyou'd like to engage someone,
p237
aVsomeone who's had the procedure.
p238
aVPatients are experts on their own experience,
p239
aVand they can share that experience with others.
p240
aVThis is the medical care that goes beyond just medicines.
p241
aa(lp242
VSo the mothers who work for us,
p243
aVthey come from the communities in which they work.
p244
aVThey're hired \u2014 they're paid as professional members of the health care teams,
p245
aVjust like doctors and nurses.
p246
aVAnd we open bank accounts for them
p247
aVand they're paid directly into the accounts,
p248
aVbecause their money's protected;
p249
aVthe men can't take it away from them.
p250
aVThey go through two to three weeks
p251
aVof rigorous curriculum-based education, training.
p252
aVNow, doctors and nurses \u2014 they too get trained.
p253
aVBut so often, they only get trained once,
p254
aVso they're not aware of new medicines,
p255
aVnew guidelines as they come out.
p256
aVOur mentor mothers get trained every single year
p257
aVand retrained.
p258
aVAnd so doctors and nurses \u2014
p259
aVthey look up to them as experts.
p260
aVImagine that: a woman, a former patient,
p261
aVbeing able to educate her doctor for the first time
p262
aVand educate the other patients
p263
aVthat she's taking care of.
p264
aa(lp265
VOur organization has three goals.
p266
aVThe first, to prevent mother-to-child transmission.
p267
aVThe second: keep mothers healthy, keep mothers alive,
p268
aVkeep the children alive \u2014
p269
aVno more orphans.
p270
aVAnd the third, and maybe the most grand,
p271
aVis to find ways to empower women,
p272
aVenable them to fight the stigma
p273
aVand to live positive and productive lives with HIV.
p274
aVSo how do we do it?
p275
aVWell, maybe the most important engagement
p276
aVis the one-to-one,
p277
aVseeing patients one-to-one, educating them, supporting them,
p278
aVexplaining how they can take care of themselves.
p279
aVWe go beyond that;
p280
aVwe try to bring in the husbands, the partners.
p281
aVIn Africa, it's very, very hard to engage men.
p282
aVMen are not frequently part of pregnancy care.
p283
aVBut in Rwanda, in one country,
p284
aVthey've got a policy
p285
aVthat a woman can't come for care
p286
aVunless she brings the father of the baby with her \u2014
p287
aVthat's the rule.
p288
aVAnd so the father and the mother, together,
p289
aVgo through the counseling and the testing.
p290
aVThe father and the mother, together, they get the results.
p291
aVAnd this is so important in breaking through the stigma.
p292
aa(lp293
VDisclosure is so central to prevention.
p294
aVHow do you have safer sex, how do you use a condom regularly
p295
aVif there hasn't been disclosure?
p296
aVDisclosure is so important to treatment,
p297
aVbecause again, people need the support of family members and friends
p298
aVto take their medicines regularly.
p299
aVWe also work in groups.
p300
aVNow the groups, it's not like me lecturing,
p301
aVbut what happens is women, they come together \u2014
p302
aVunder the support and guidance of our mentor mothers \u2014
p303
aVthey come together, and they share their personal experiences.
p304
aVAnd it's through the sharing
p305
aVthat people get tactics of how to take care of themselves,
p306
aVhow to disclose how to take medicines.
p307
aVAnd then there's the community outreach,
p308
aVengaging women in their communities.
p309
aVIf we can change the way
p310
aVhouseholds believe and think,
p311
aVwe can change the way communities believe and think.
p312
aVAnd if we can change enough communities,
p313
aVwe can change national attitudes.
p314
aVWe can change national attitudes to women
p315
aVand national attitudes to HIV.
p316
aVThe hardest barrier really is around stigma reduction.
p317
aVWe have the medicines, we have the tests,
p318
aVbut how do you reduce the stigma?
p319
aVAnd it's important about disclosure.
p320
aa(lp321
VSo, a couple years ago, one of the mentor mothers came back,
p322
aVand she told me a story.
p323
aVShe had been asked by one of the clients
p324
aVto go to the home of the client,
p325
aVbecause the client wanted to tell the mother and her brothers and sisters
p326
aVabout her HIV status,
p327
aVand she was afraid to go by herself.
p328
aVAnd so the mentor mother went along with.
p329
aVAnd the patient walked into the house
p330
aVand said to her mother and siblings,
p331
aV"I have something to tell you. I'm HIV-positive."
p332
aVAnd everybody was quiet.
p333
aVAnd then her oldest brother stood up and said,
p334
aV"I too have something to tell you.
p335
aVI'm HIV-positive.
p336
aVI've been afraid to tell everybody."
p337
aVAnd then this older sister stood up and said,
p338
aV"I too am living with the virus,
p339
aVand I've been ashamed."
p340
aVAnd then her younger brother stood up and said,
p341
aV"I'm also positive.
p342
aVI thought you were going to throw me out of the family."
p343
aVAnd you see where this is going.
p344
aVThe last sister stood up and said, "I'm also positive.
p345
aVI thought you were going to hate me."
p346
aVAnd there they were, all of them together for the first time
p347
aVbeing able to share this experience for the first time
p348
aVand to support each other for the first time.
